And the Uſe of Ediſices being various, it was
neceſſary to enquire whether one and the ſame Kind of Deſign was fit for all Sorts of Buildings;
upon which Account we have diſtinguiſhed the ſeveral Kinds of Buildings: Wherein perceiv­
ing that the main Point was the juſt Compoſition and Relation of the Lines among themſelves,
from whence ariſes the Height of Beauty, I therefore began to examine what Beauty really was,
and what Sort of Beauty was proper to each Edifice.

CHAP. II. Of the firſt Occaſion of erecting Edifices;
of how many Parts the Art of Building conſiſts, and
what is neceſſary to each of thoſe Parts.

CHAP. XIII. Of the Stair-caſes, and their different Sorts;
of Steps of the Stairs which ought to be in odd Numbers,
and how many.

CHAP. XI. Of the Way of Working different Materials;
of Plaiſtering, of Cramps, and how to preſerve them;
the moſt ancient Inſtructions of Architects; and ſome
Methods to prevent the Miſchiefs of Lightning.

Of the
Caſtles or Habitations of a King, or others;
their different Properties and Parts.

CHAP. XIV. Of private Houſes and their Differences;
as alſo of the Country Houſe, and the Rules to be obſerved
in its Situation and Structure.

CHAP. XVII. Of the Country Houſe for a Gentleman;
its various Parts, and the proper Diſpoſition of each of
thoſe Parts.

Among the Ægyp­
tians there are Royal Palaces built of Ruſhes;
and in India, of the Ribs of Whales.

Laſtly, the Ancients,
for this Sort of Work greatly commend Flints,
and eſpecially thoſe which are fulleſt of Holes;
not becauſe ſuch are the ſtrongeſt, but becauſe
they are the leaſt ſlippery.

The North-wind is leſs prejudicial
than the South to all Stores of Seeds and Fruits;
but any Wind whatſoever blowing from damp
Places will fill them with Maggots and Worms;
andany conſtant impetuous Wind willmake them
ſhrivelled and withered.

Of the Defects in Buildings, whence they proceed, and their different Sorts;
which of them can be corrected by the Architect, and which cannot; and the
various Cauſes of a bad Air.

I shall now proceed to the Remedies for ſome
other Inconveniencies of ſmaller Moment;
in which I ſhall be as brief as poſſible.

The Ceiling of this Parlour ſhould be arched;
and then you will be ſurprized how warm it
will be in Winter and how cold in Summer.
